On february 7, 2013
[4978404]

Why? Armor works nice against light weapons. Think about this example:

Sai. Damage = 15.
4 hits= 15x4= 60
4 hits with armor= (15-5)x4= 40
Armor reduced 33% of incoming damage.

Bumps. Damage= 50
1 hit= 50
1 hit with armor= 45
Armor reduced 10% of incoming damage.

As you can see, it will work better as less damage as you would suffer without armor. Also protects your from dog and wolf damage. Since all brutes eventually get high strength, it will be probably less useful as you level up.

Thanks

No, the backup can only be used if your OTHER brute is higher. So you main brute will never be able to use it unless the backup brute becomes higher level than him. The ability button will be active, but if you click on it and then fight with your other brute, you won't join the fight.


This is how it works:


Brute 1: lower level than brute2, and has backup.
Brute 2: higher level than brute 1.


Brute 1 clicks on "backup" button.
Brute 2 starts a fight.
Brute 1 will join the fight around 40% of your health.

the damage with 30 speed against 30 str comes out in strs favour by a bit (REALLY its not much) but its obviously better to attack more than to do a bit more damage each turn. why? cause you will have much more time to shock, sabotage and use supers.

well that's what i'm saying not to do in my previous post. Do not compare X amount of speed to X amount of str. Instead compare the further gains of Y amount of speed to the further gains of Y amount of str, think taking the derivative in calculus.
Sure 30 speed might be better than 30 str, but what are the benefits of adding 10 additional speed/str. adding 20? adding 100? As you go further down, the benefits of adding additional speed decreases while the benefit of adding strength stays constant.

L1berty:

Just a theory about backup brutes (dunno if I've posted this before, but meh)

When they appear, they have a fixed amount of initiative (which is likely to be affected by their "natural" starting initiative, along with some combination of their other stats), and will attack until the initiative points run out. Damaging a backup brute will lower their initiative pool


This theory somewhat explains the backup glitch, since I see that glitch as a backup brute with unlimited initiative points (so they can keep attacking and keep getting damaged indefinitely)
